{{Item|itemImage=Icon-bauxite-residue.png|research=Gold Refining|sellValue={{Money|50}}|resValue={{RP|1x }}}}
==Information==
'''Bauxite Residue''' is created by inputting [[Soil]] or [[Deep Earth Fragment]] into a [[Trommel]]. It is necessary for the creation of [[Aluminium Ingot]].

Another way to get it is to use the [[Industrial Drill]]. Power it with [[Steam]], and select '''Bauxite Residue''' in the terminal. (Exclusive to worlds with '''[[Ore Nodes]]''')

It can be also extracted using the [[Mineshaft Drill]].

It is the primary resource in starting [[Aluminium Ingot|Aluminium ingots]], along with the entire electronics production.

===Aluminium Ingot===
# Insert it into the [[Grinder]] to turn it into [[Crushed Bauxite]].
# Chuck it into a [[Blast Furnace]] along with some [[Coke Fuel]] to make [[Alumina]].
# Put the [[Alumina]] back into the [[Grinder]] to make [[Alumina Dust]].
# Now melt the [[Alumina Dust]] into the [[Industrial Electric Furnace]] (It cannot be done with a regular [[Electric Furnace]]. Only by using latter) to make [[Liquid Aluminium]].
# And finally, right into the [[Ingot Molder]] to make [[Aluminium Ingot]].

=== Ferroaluminium Magnet ===
# Combine an [[Iron Ingot]], an [[Aluminium Ingot]] and [[Steam]] in an [[Alloyer]] to make [[Molten Ferroaluminium Alloy]].
# Pipe it into an [[Ingot Molder]] to make [[Ferroaluminium Alloy Ingot]].
# Take it into an [[Industrial Roller]] (not [[Roller]]) to make [[Ferroaluminium Magnet]].

=== Semiconductor ===

# Combine [[Silicon]] and [[Aluminium Ingot]] in a [[Precision Assembler]] to make [[Semiconductor]], used in [[Microchip]] production.

==Usage==
'''Bauxite Residue''' is produced by the [[Trommel]] and has only one use, to be ground and refined into [[Aluminium Ingot|Aluminium]]. Note that if the player is making [[Purple Gold Ingot|Purple Gold]] with the same [[Trommel|Trommels]] the player may expect a small overflow with producing more [[Aluminium Ingot|Aluminium ingots]] than the player need, so simply sell the excess if it happens.

